Use MAUI's **lifecycle events** (`OnSleep` / `OnResume`) paired with **`Preferences`** for lightweight storage:

**In your `App.xaml.cs`:**
```csharp
protected override void OnSleep()
{
    // Fire a message so the page can save its state
    WeakReferenceMessenger.Default.Send(new AppSleepMessage());
}
```

**In your Notes page (ViewModel or code-behind):**
```csharp
using CommunityToolkit.Mvvm.Messaging;

public NotesPage()
{
    InitializeComponent();

    // Save draft when app backgrounds
    WeakReferenceMessenger.Default.Register<AppSleepMessage>(this, (r, m) =>
    {
        Preferences.Set("draft_note", NoteEditor.Text ?? string.Empty);
    });

    // Restore draft on page load
    if (Preferences.ContainsKey("draft_note"))
    {
        NoteEditor.Text = Preferences.Get("draft_note", string.Empty);
    }
}

// Clean up when the note is explicitly saved/discarded
private void OnNoteSaved()
{
    Preferences.Remove("draft_note");
}
```

**Define the message class:**
```csharp
public class AppSleepMessage { }
```

**Key points:**
- **`Preferences`** persists across app restarts — handles force-kills too.
- **`WeakReferenceMessenger`** (from `CommunityToolkit.Mvvm`) decouples `App` from the page.
- Call `Preferences.Remove("draft_note")` when the user intentionally saves or discards, so stale drafts don't reappear.
- For large text, swap `Preferences` for `SecureStorage` or a file via `FileSystem.AppDataDirectory`.
